{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640039"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:11:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:11:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17796"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17796","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17796"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.56,0.1,0.05,0.22,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10510"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79261"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10510"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17796"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64595"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9930"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24534"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25018"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79261","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79261"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe respiratory centre in the brainstem contains specialised neurons that monitor and regulate breathing rate and depth. These central chemoreceptors are located on the ventrolateral surface of the medulla.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary stimulus detected by central chemoreceptors?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Changes in cerebrospinal fluid pH","Changes in arterial oxygen tension","Changes in blood pH","Changes in blood carbon dioxide tension","Changes in cerebrospinal fluid bicarbonate"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECentral chemoreceptors respond primarily to \u003Cstrong\u003Echanges in cerebrospinal fluid pH\u003C/strong\u003E. These receptors are located on the ventrolateral surface of the medulla and are separated from the blood by the blood-brain barrier. When arterial carbon dioxide rises, it readily diffuses across the blood-brain barrier and combines with water to form carbonic acid, which dissociates to hydrogen ions and bicarbonate, thereby lowering cerebrospinal fluid pH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChanges in arterial oxygen tension\u003C/strong\u003E - This is detected by peripheral chemoreceptors in the carotid and aortic bodies\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChanges in blood pH\u003C/strong\u003E - Blood pH changes do not directly affect central chemoreceptors due to the blood-brain barrier\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChanges in blood carbon dioxide tension\u003C/strong\u003E - Carbon dioxide must first affect cerebrospinal fluid pH to stimulate central chemoreceptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChanges in cerebrospinal fluid bicarbonate\u003C/strong\u003E - While bicarbonate changes occur, it is the pH change that stimulates the receptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECentral chemoreceptors are responsible for approximately 80% of the ventilatory response to hypercapnia, making them the primary drivers of respiratory control.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Central chemoreceptors in the medulla detect changes in cerebrospinal fluid pH to regulate breathing.","Carbon dioxide readily crosses the blood-brain barrier and affects cerebrospinal fluid pH through the formation of carbonic acid.","Central chemoreceptors are primarily responsible for respiratory drive, accounting for about 80% of the ventilatory response to hypercapnia."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64595"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17796"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64595"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T21:14:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T21:20:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10510"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79261"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/